SKILL|llama-cpp|llama.cpp local GGUF inference + HF Hub model discovery.
STEP|1|Run local models on CPU, Apple Silicon, CUDA, ROCm, or Intel GPUs
STEP|2|Find the right GGUF for a specific Hugging Face repo
STEP|3|Build a `llama-server` or `llama-cli` command from the Hub
STEP|4|Search the Hub for models that already support llama.cpp
STEP|5|Enumerate available `.gguf` files and sizes for a repo
STEP|6|Decide between Q4/Q5/Q6/IQ variants for the user's RAM or VRAM
STEP|7|Search for candidate repos on the Hub:
STEP|8|Open the repo with the llama.cpp local-app view:
STEP|9|Treat the local-app snippet as the source of truth when it is visible:
STEP|10|Read the same `?local-app=llama.cpp` URL as page text or HTML and extract the section under `Hardware compatibility`:
STEP|11|Query the tree API to confirm what actually exists:
STEP|12|If the local-app snippet is not text-visible, reconstruct the command from the repo plus the chosen quant:
STEP|13|Only suggest conversion from Transformers weights if the repo does not already expose GGUF files.
STEP|14|Prefer the exact quant that HF marks as compatible for the user's hardware profile.
STEP|15|For general chat, start with `Q4_K_M`.
STEP|16|For code or technical work, prefer `Q5_K_M` or `Q6_K` if memory allows.
STEP|17|For very tight RAM budgets, consider `Q3_K_M`, `IQ` variants, or `Q2` variants only if the user explicitly prioritizes fit over quality.
STEP|18|For multimodal repos, mention `mmproj-*.gguf` separately. The projector is not the main model file.
STEP|19|Do not normalize repo-native labels. If the page says `UD-Q4_K_M`, report `UD-Q4_K_M`.
STEP|20|filename
STEP|21|file size
